 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f7f7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/uugle.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ugle</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Dubious Poster</span><br>  Posts: 134<br> <font color=#778899>(10/29/01 2:43:42 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://ugleduklin.tripod.com/sitebuildercontent/sitebuilderpictures/dscn0011s.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Summit Clarification: Small Guilds</span><hr size=1> This is really meant to address one of the bigger complaints the larger Guilds had about the Planes.  If a Guild with 70 people followed the rules, they would get their 2 bookings a month.  If 7 Guilds with 10 people booked the Planes and went up together, potentially you would have 14 bookings a month.  Though I think the amount of abuse of the previous rules was a whole lot smaller then some of the big guilds claimed, it could be exploited.  <br>
<br>
And lets be honest.  Most Guilds of 10-20 people aren't full of L60's.  Most L60's want to be doing ToV and Dain and other Boss MOB's that require more people then that.  I'm sure someone is gonna say otherwise, but I sincerely doubt a Guild of 15 people is gonna be balanced and high-level enough to break and clear the Planes.  15 people could do it, but usually with inviting friends and stuff you end up lacking in some classes with the smaller Guilds.<br>
<br>
How about we make a new rule then Aldrin?  Nobody that is not part of the booking Guild can go on days that are scheduled.  That way you can screw over the unguilded even more.  Lots of Guilds have been doing joint bookings, but you know if you keep this up long enough you can make it even harder for the unguilded to get a chance to go to the Planes, WTG.  I'm not seeing any other unguilded people on here flaming, because they make friends and probably get to go to the Planes more then quite a few of the people in Guilds do.  But it's a lot easier to biatch then try to get along isn't it? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f7f7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/uhiraghm.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Hiraghm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Indifferent Poster</span><br>  Posts: 277<br> <font color=#778899>(10/29/01 3:07:23 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.home.com/jdwilliams2/data/Aldrinshroom1.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Summit Clarification: Small Guilds</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> How about we make a new rule then Aldrin? Nobody that is not part of the booking Guild can go on days that are scheduled. That way you can screw over the unguilded even more. Lots of Guilds have been doing joint bookings, but you know if you keep this up long enough you can make it even harder for the unguilded to get a chance to go to the Planes, WTG. I'm not seeing any other unguilded people on here flaming, because they make friends and probably get to go to the Planes more then quite a few of the people in Guilds do. But it's a lot easier to biatch then try to get along isn't it? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Of course it's bad if you leave it at that, and that wasn't my proposal, either. How about having a rule whereby if you don't need something from a plane (specifically, epic drops) you don't go? That's silly, but here's the situation as I see it from what's been argued in the past:<br>
The big guilds want epics for their members.<br>
The smaller guilds also want epics, but also want some of the other drops<br>
But not everybody in every guild is going to need his epic drop at the same time, are they? Some will have it already, some won't need it for awhile... So why should, say, all of TD, or even half, have to occupy a plane, even if they allow guests? You've set up a calendar for assigning the plane, how about a system whereby those in the various guilds who need epic drops and are at a point where they need them go on raids with those in other guilds who need epic drops and are where they need them? While the rest of the guilds go play in places they'd rather be at anyway? True, an epic drop won't drop for every person who wants one every time, but that's not guaranteed with a guild raid, either. <br>
<br>
Rather than dismissing this idea, think about ways it could be made to work, or problems that would have to be addressed for it to work. And *then* tell me what a load of dingo's kidneys it is.... AND WHY.<br>
<br>
Aldrin Moonwalker(and no, it's much much harder to stand up for principles than just go along to get along...)<br>
